AVIAN INFLUENZA (11): SOUTH KOREA (SOUTH CHUNGCHEONG) HPAI H5N8, CHICKEN, SPREAD, CONTROL
*****************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sat 25 Jan 2014
Source: Yonhapnews [summarised, edited]
http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/search1/2603000000.html?cid=AEN20140125001552315


Health authorities have confirmed bird flu in a chicken and in the feces of migratory birds. Cases of avian influenza [AI] reported so far all involved ducks. The latest case involving a chicken was reported at a farm in Buyeo, a town about 150 km from where the poultry disease was 1st detected at a duck farm in North Jeolla Province a week ago.

The Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Affairs said it has found that the infected chicken contains the H5N8 strain of the virus. It marked the 1st time that the H5N8 strain has been found in a chicken.

Later on Saturday [25 Jan 2014], officials in the populous Gyeonggi Province, a region surrounding Seoul, said feces recovered from around Sihwa Lake in Hwaseong, on the province's west coast just south of Seoul, also contained AI. They said they could conclude by as early as Sunday [26 Jan 2014] whether the strain is the highly pathogenic strain.

The province has designated the area within a 10-km radius of the lake as a quarantine zone, restricting entries of poultry and vehicles, officials said.

The confirmation from the poultry farm in Buyeo is expected to expand the scope of precautionary culling to cover chickens [see items 2, 3]. Only ducks had been slaughtered as a preventive step after the highly pathogenic strain of bird flu was found among a group of migratory birds found dead on 17 Jan 2014 at a reservoir near affected farms in North Jeolla Province. Authorities believe they may have been the carriers of the virus.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

******
[2]
Date: Sun 26 Jan 2014
Source: Korea Herald [edited]
http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140126000223


The government is considering imposing a lockdown at all poultry farms throughout the country as avian influenza is showing signs of further spreading, officials said on Sunday [26 Jan 2014].

A nationwide lockdown, if issued, will prohibit the movement of any poultry, workers, or vehicles from farms for 48 hours. Such a move can be extended once for another 48 hours.

Such a move will create what health authorities here have called a "window of opportunity" to sterilize all poultry farms at the same time and thus prevent a further spread of the disease.

The consideration for such a move apparently comes as the animal disease is fast spreading to surrounding areas from Gochang in North Jeolla Province, where the 1st outbreak of AI was confirmed on 17 Jan 2014. The government had imposed a 48-hour lockdown at all poultry farms in Gochang soon after the 1st outbreak of AI was confirmed.

The number of confirmed AI cases has since reached 18 with the highly pathogenic H5N8 strain of the virus confirmed in the latest case at a chicken farm in Buyeo, South Chungcheong Province on Saturday [25 Jan 2014].

A new suspected case was reported earlier in the day at a duck farm in Cheonnan, located only some 80 km south of Seoul, the Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Affairs said in a press release. Tests were underway in an additional 21 suspected cases as of Sunday [26 Jan 2014].

Some 470 000 birds, mostly ducks, have been slaughtered so far. Over 1.74 million others are set to be culled as the government has decided to also destroy chickens at all farms within 3 km from affected farms after it confirmed the 1st outbreak of bird flu in chickens on Saturday [25 Jan 2014].

